So the change is a one-line fix in `scripts/preseed_session_plan.py`: changing the word-matching from a substring check (`any(word in lower for word in ...)`) to a word-boundary regex search (`re.search(r'\b(?:flaky|fail|failed|error|retry)\b', lower)`). 

The problem was that the substring match would match "fail" inside words like "failure" or common words containing "error" etc. The word-boundary match fixes this. But wait — "failed" and "fail" — if we're matching "fail" with \b, that would match "fail" but not "failed". So the substitution would mean "fail" only matches the word "fail", not "failed". But "failed" is still in the list. Let me think about what the original bug was...

Actually, the issue was likely the opposite: "error" as a substring would match "error_message", "errors", etc. — or more specifically, "fail" as a substring would match in unexpected places. The word-boundary fix makes each word match only as a whole word.

Looking at the context of the function `_self_tests_show_resolution`: This checks whether self-test result lines show task-domain features already working. Lines containing failure-related words (flaky, fail, failed, error, retry) are skipped because they indicate something not working. With the old substring match, "fail" would also match "failure" — but that seems mostly ok, since "failure" is also a failure signal. 

The actual bug mentioned in the commit: "word-boundary match for fail in self-test resolution check." Perhaps the issue was that "fail" was matching something like "failover" or "unfail"? Or maybe the issue was more subtle — "error" could match "without_error" or similar constructs in test output that are actually success messages.

In any case, this was a one-line, one-character-change fix (well, a few characters). The task picker detected stale-task detection was broken because of this matching issue.

