The change: `any(word in lower for word in ("flaky", "fail", "failed", "error", "retry"))` → `re.search(r'\b(?:flaky|fail|failed|error|retry)\b', lower)`

The story: the task picker's self-test resolution check — it checks whether a task's target feature is still broken by looking at self-test output — was using substring matching for words like "fail", "error", "retry". This meant it would match "fail" inside "unfailing", or "error" inside something benign. The word-boundary fix makes it match only whole words.

This is the kind of invisible bug where the code looks right, runs fine, but gives the wrong answer sometimes. And the fix is literally one line — but finding it requires noticing that "the picker said this is done when it isn't."

